        <div class="col-md-12">
          <div class="why-behavior-wrap">
            <p>
              Why Behavior? Unraveling what drives human beliefs, attitudes and actions is a complex task.  We have subconscious mechanisms which play havoc with our ability to make rational decisions, despite our best intentions. Our tendencies to underestimate risk, interpret facts incorrectly, and live at odds with our values are just a few examples of how these mechanisms affect us.
            </p>
            <p>
              These cognitive foibles are especially obvious when it comes to environmental issues; we individually and collectively continue to make destructive choices that degrade the planetary systems we need to sustain us.  Many environmental campaigns are based on the erroneous assumption that we can simply raise awareness to encourage behavior change, and that once a solution has been developed it will simply “catch on” at a large scale.  Environmental organizations need conservation solutions that are scaled to the environmental problems they face.  Research shows that providing information alone is not enough to change public behavior – we need to find conservation solutions that work directly with how humans think, act, and make decisions.
            </p>
            <p>
              When environmental champions lack the expertise to effectively overcome mental barriers and persuade people to adopt needed changes, they can turn to behavioral science and behavioral economics. These disciplines explore how people process information and make decisions. "Behavioral Insights” are proven, effective tools for aligning behaviors with sustainability on both the individual and collective level.
            </p>
            <p>
              Scientists have highlighted the need for the urgent transformation of our social, economic and industrial systems to create a prosperous, resilient future. We have developed the technological solutions necessary, and will continue to innovate.
            </p>
            <p>
              Now it is time to embrace another type of innovation – social innovation. We have the opportunity to use all that we understand about our own behavior to solve the psychological, social and institutional roadblocks that are our largest challenges. Behavioral science is a proven and promising approach to improving environmental initiatives, and Root Solutions’ mission is to build the behavioral science capacity within the environmental community.
            </p>
            <p>
              Below is an in depth look at the mental challenges we face. Learn more about the solutions that allow us to overcome these challenges and bring about pro-environmental actions here.
            </p>
          </div> <!-- why-behavior-wrap -->
        </div> <!-- col-md-12 -->
      </div> <!-- col-md-8 -->
    </div> <!-- header-row row -->
    <div id="why-behavior-parallax" class="heading-title">
      <h2 class="other-titles">
        Automatic Thinking
      </h2>
    </div>
    <div class="row">
      <div class='col-md-2'></div>
      <div class='col-md-8'>
        <div class="col-md-12">
          <div class="automatic-thinking-wrap">
  ​          <blockquote>
              <p>
                <h3 class="why-behavior-header-three">
                  Attention and energy are needed for making judgments and taking actions, but both are finite
                </h3>
              </p>
            </blockquote>
            <p>
              At any given moment, we have a finite amount of attention at our disposal. We automatically conserve our limited attention for those tasks that seem pressing.  In the process we may forget to do other important things with benefits that don’t materialize until the future. Additionally, when attention is stretched, people have a difficult time focusing on both the benefits and costs of options, making rational decisions nearly impossible to make. These errors of omission can have serious consequences.
            </p>
            <p>
              Furthermore, when we’re focused on completing a task or understanding a piece of information we may not notice other things going on around us, even if those things are unusual or important. This “inattentional blindness” was clearly demonstrated in a landmark study called the Invisible Gorilla Test. Participants were given an effortful task designed to take up their attention (e.g., count the number of times a basketball was passed in a video). While they focused on this task, a woman walked through the background of the video – either holding an umbrella, or wearing a full gorilla suit. As many as 50% of the subjects didn’t notice the woman, either with the umbrella OR wearing the suit.
            </p>
            <p>
              This phenomenon of having only limited attention impacts our daily lives and shapes the decisions we make by limiting the amount of information we have to base them on. We also experience a phenomenon called “decision fatigue” or “choice overload” when we’re presented with too many options or too much information. This can cause us to give up and avoid making a choice all together. Furthermore, it takes a lot of mental energy to acquire and habitualize new behaviors. During this process we must use our System 2 thinking, and so we become subject to cognitive fatigue. As we become skilled at or accustomed to something, the effort associated with performing the action goes down (we experience cognitive ease).  When a problem appears to be easy, we tend to use System 1, expending much less energy but making us more prone to logical errors.  When a task creates a small amount of strain (such as if you had to read a trick question but it was smudged, forcing you to put more effort into decoding the words) you are more likely to answer correctly. 
            </p>
            <p>
              Self-control also draws upon a limited pool of mental resources that can be used up. When we lack self-control we are less likely to successfully achieve our own behavior change goals. Small barriers to completing a given behavior can disproportionately reduce the likelihood that we’ll follow through. Because of our constant subconscious quest to preserve our energy and seek out the easiest options, trivial obstacles (“hassle factors”) like having to wait in a line or fill out a form are enough to halt behavior change.
            </p>
            <blockquote>
              <p>
                <h3 class="why-behavior-header-three">
                  We rely on predictable cognitive biases and heuristics that lead us astray
                </h3>
              </p>
            </blockquote>
            <p>
              Making decisions requires cognitive effort. As decisions become more difficult, we tend to take the path of least resistance by reducing the amount of effort that we invest in making a choice.  We have evolved a whole host of subconscious cognitive tricks that help us make decisions quickly, thereby conserving energy and allowing us to stick to our System 1 thinking processes. There are potentially thousands of details that could be observed in any given situation. Because we have limited mental energy to devote to decision-making on a day to day basis we use mental shortcuts, called “heuristics”, to help us problem solve without having to spend time searching for all the necessary information and weighing the costs and benefits.  These heuristics can be very useful for helping us process a large amount of stimuli and information quickly, but they can also lead to predictable errors in reasoning, judgment and decision-making.  These predictable errors are called cognitive biases and they distort our perceptions.
            </p>
            <p>
              For example, we often see patterns where none exist (representativeness heuristic), allow our current emotional state to influence our decisions (affect heuristic), and ignore “general” information, like statistics, that pertain to large groups, and focus instead on “specific” information that may only pertain to an individual case (base rate fallacy). We also tend to overestimate the significance of information that appears especially immediate, vivid, or tangible (availability heuristic). This means that we tend to think that an event—such as, for instance, a massive storm or flood—is more likely when we can readily think of examples of such an event happening in the past, and events seem less likely if we don’t associate them with a vivid mental image. Furthermore, we over-value the opinions of people who we believe to be experts or authority figures (authority and expert heuristic), we favor the opinions of people who are similar to us over people who we consider to be “outsiders” (in-group bias), and we assume that people’s actions result in morally fair consequences, so that any situation a person is in must be fitting and justified (just world fallacy). These biases and heuristics can be problematic because they often encourage us to focus in on the most eye-catching readily palpable aspects of an issue, blinding us to its larger, more complex, or more difficult to digest causes and repercussions. However countering their effects can be as simple as increasing people’s awareness of them just before asking them to make decisions or take in new information.
            </p>
            <div class="why-behavior-more-resources">
              <h4>More resources</h4>
              <ul class="why-behavior-resources" style="font-size:18px">
                <li>
                  <%= link_to "Brain Biases Blog", "http://brainshortcuts.blogspot.com/", target: "_blank" %>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <%= link_to "World Bank Report 2015 – Mind, Society, and Behavior: Chapter 1", "http://www.worldbank.org/404_response.htm", target: "_blank" %>
                </li>
              </ul> <!-- why-behavior-resources -->
            </div> <!-- why-behavior-more-resources -->
          </div> <!-- automatic-thinking-wrap -->
        </div> <!-- col-md-12 -->
      </div> <!-- col-md-8 -->
