    <div id="why-behavior-parallax" class="heading-title">
      <h2 class="other-titles">Social Thinking</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="row">
      <div class='col-md-2'></div>
      <div class='col-md-8'>
        <div class="col-md-12">
          <div class="social-thinking-wrap">
            <blockquote>
              <p>
                <h3 class="why-behavior-header-three">
                  Our sense of self profoundly shapes our behaviors and choices
                </h3>
              </p>
            </blockquote>
            <p>
              Our choices are profoundly impacted by our sense of self. We desire to see ourselves, and for others to see us, as “good people” who do the right thing, make educated choices, and don’t waiver in our commitments over time. We want to appear consistent with our past selves and our public promises – this is why asking for a public commitment is so powerful for eliciting desired behaviors (see side box?). We also act in ways that make us feel better about ourselves. After engaging in a behavior we judge to be “bad” (for ourselves or for others) we are driven to engage in “good” or “moral” behaviors to offset our negative feelings. For example, after driving to work rather than commuting in a more sustainable manner (e.g., riding a bike, taking the bus) we may be more likely to make a sustainable choice at lunch time to alleviate our feeling of environmental guilt. However, there’s a flip side to this “moral cleansing” coin wherein we often feel authorized to engage in “bad” behaviors after we’ve done something “good”.  This “moral licensing” is a common problem encountered in home efficiency programs—those who save a lot of energy one month may feel that they have licensed themselves to use more energy the next month.
            </p>​
            <p>​
              Our sense of self is also highly impacted by our perception of how meaningful our actions are. We lose motivation if we believe that our actions are not making a difference.  For example, if an environmental group attempts to address a conservation problem in a community, but fails to follow through, allowing the problem to persist or return after the initial intervention, the community will be less inclined to work with the next environmental group that attempts to address that issue (i.e. they experience Conservation Fatigue). Relatedly, the more effort we put into something inspired by a belief, the stronger our convictions will be about that belief (effort justification, or “the Ikea effect”). For example, working to raise money or support for a project or campaign makes us more resolute in our beliefs about the value of the cause or candidate we’re supporting.
            </p>
            <blockquote>
              <p>
                <h3 class="why-behavior-header-three">
                  Our understanding of our relationship to society and community also profoundly shapes our behaviors and choices
                </h3>
              </p>
            </blockquote>
            <p>
              In addition to our sense of self, our perceptions and beliefs about our role in society and our social networks can significantly influence our actions. Social expectations, the desire for recognition, care for in-group members, and social norms all influence our behavior without our conscious awareness. People are “social animals” by nature. We tend to care what other people think of us, and we are strongly influenced by social pressures. The networks and groups that we are members of dictate many of the choices we make because we look to others for examples of the best ways to behave and we strive to fit in. Furthermore, adopting the opinions and behaviors of the majority is a way to feel safe when we’re forced to make decisions about which we may not be well-informed (social proof heuristic). Studies have shown that the likelihood that someone will choose a specific option is directly proportional to the number of other individuals who’ve already chosen it (i.e. bandwagon effect, conformity experiments).
            </p>
            <p>
              However, sometimes we are mistaken about the prevalence of a given behavior or belief in our societies. When considering beliefs, or behaviors that may not be performed publically, we may assume that our belief is in line with the social norm when in fact it is not. Thus, negative behaviors can be subconsciously reinforced by social norms even when there are none. Helping people to recognize these incorrect assumptions (for example, publishing statistics on the prevalence of the belief that climate change is an important issue among a specific audience) can be a powerful motivator of behavior change. Relatedly, we often assume that the beliefs of one member of a group (our own or another) are representative of the whole group, or that the outcome of a group decision reflects the personal beliefs of every member of the group. These “group attribution errors” can lead to polarization that can undermine efforts to move towards consensus on necessary behavior changes.
            </p>
